<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="440" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,760,190,2069]" lastBlockId="3.[828,1437,190,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,413,1982,2005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Having venter primarily dark colored, but abdomen lightly colored, the new species is included in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[320,467,2046,2069]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[320,467,2046,2069]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. 
<taxonomicName authority="Short &amp; Benetti &amp; Gustafson, 2020" authorityName="Short &amp; Benetti &amp; Gustafson" authorityYear="2020" box="[637,905,190,2069]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[637,905,190,2069]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Platynectes bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[912,994,190,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[1193,1338,190,213]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[1193,1338,190,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having a darkly colored venter with orange abdomen, and elytra with four yellow maculae. However, it can readily be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[999,1141,286,309]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[999,1141,286,309]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by being smaller in size (6.0 mm compared to 
<quantity box="[1011,1107,318,341]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.25" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" unit="mm" value="7.25">7.25 mm</quantity>
) and having an evenly rounded habitus, compared to the more elongate oval appearance of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[855,997,382,405]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[855,997,382,405]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, the pronotal lateral margins of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Short &amp; Benetti &amp; Gustafson" authorityYear="2020" box="[857,960,414,437]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[857,960,414,437]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are straighter relatively to the more strongly arced and rounded appearing pronotal margins of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Finally, the elytral discal punctures forming a series of lines (serial punctures) that are present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[1292,1436,510,533]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[1292,1436,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Short &amp; Benetti &amp; Gustafson" authorityYear="2020" box="[970,1074,542,565]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[970,1074,542,565]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, being obscured by denser elytral sculpturing. This latter character (‘subserial punctures’ easily distinguished) was used as a diagnostic feature by SIJΑ*©Ρ (1882) for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[1020,1165,638,661]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[1020,1165,638,661]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">P. ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="440" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[828,1437,190,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,955,670,693]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Etymology.</emphasis>
An adjective 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Short &amp; Benetti &amp; Gustafson" authorityYear="2020" box="[1094,1170,670,693]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Platynectes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[1094,1170,670,693]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[= two-colored] referring to the contrasting coloration of the dorsal and ventral surfaces of the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[828,1437,190,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,922,766,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Habitat.</emphasis>
Both series of specimens were collected from similar habitats: from small pools in rock with root mats near streams. The specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[1182,1243,830,853]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Goiás</collectingRegion>
were not collected in the main river, but in a small side trickle over rock that also contained significant rootmat growth (
<figureCitation box="[1293,1375,894,917]" captionStart="Figs 10–11" captionStartId="6.[151,188,683,702]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,667]" captionTargetId="figure-776@6.[151,1436,187,667]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 10–11. Habitat of Platynectes bicolor sp. nov. 10 – Brazil: Goiás, collecting event BR18-0221-01B; 11 – Brazil: Mato Grosso do Sul, collecting event BR18-0622-03D.Arrows indicate rootmat microhabitat where specimens were collected.The water was clear in both stream-seepages; the pictures were taken after the water was muddied by collecting efforts." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4489374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4489374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). The specimen from 
<collectingRegion box="[986,1120,926,949]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
do Sur was collected by taking rootmat growing on rock in a side seepage and washing it in a pan of water (
<figureCitation box="[1021,1099,990,1013]" captionStart="Figs 10–11" captionStartId="6.[151,188,683,702]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,667]" captionTargetId="figure-776@6.[151,1436,187,667]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 10–11. Habitat of Platynectes bicolor sp. nov. 10 – Brazil: Goiás, collecting event BR18-0221-01B; 11 – Brazil: Mato Grosso do Sul, collecting event BR18-0622-03D.Arrows indicate rootmat microhabitat where specimens were collected.The water was clear in both stream-seepages; the pictures were taken after the water was muddied by collecting efforts." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4489374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4489374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="440" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[828,1437,190,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,977,1022,1045]" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known from two distant localities (
<figureCitation box="[934,1008,1054,1077]" captionStart="Figs 12–16" captionStartId="7.[151,188,2029,2048]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,190,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1437,191,1857]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 12–16. Distribution of Platynectes ‘Clade II’ sensu TƟUඌඌΑιΝτ et al. (2017) in South America. Circles represent previously published localities; stars represent localities newly reported in this paper." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4489378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4489378/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="440">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) but both situated on the Brazilian Shield.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
